-- Boeing, NTT Data, Bertram Capital, Detroit's WADL: Intellectual Property
-- Victoria Slind-Flor
-- 2010-07-15T11:01:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-15/boeing-ntt-data-bertram-capital-detroit-s-wadl-intellectual-property.html

          
          
             Boeing Co. , whose composite-plastic
787 Dreamliner aircraft survived its first lightning strike in
June, received a patent on a construction method to improve
lightning-strike protection.  
 Patent 7,755,876, one of  5,094 U.S. patents  issued July 13,
covers a fastening assembly to be used on composite structures
that will reduce or eliminate internal sparking and prevent hot
gas from escaping into the structure when it is hit by
lightning.  
 According to the patent, composite materials, such as those
used on the 787, don’t normally disperse current from lightning
as evenly in an aircraft body as metals such as aluminum do. A
lightning strike near an ordinary fastener can quickly produce a
high current density entering the body of the aircraft through
the fastener.  
 A key element of the patented fastener is a washer that can
contain hot gasses and prevent arcing.  
 Chicago-based Boeing applied for this patent in June 2007
with the assistance of Law Office of Charles W. Peterson Jr. of
Herndon, Virginia.  
 NTT Data Says It Will Investigate Actions of Arrested Employee  
 NTT Data Corp. , a provider of networking system services,
said it will investigate the actions of an employee who was
arrested on suspicion of bribing a patent office worker.  
 The Tokyo-based company, which confirmed the arrest on June
22, said it will seek to restore public trust. It released
yesterday’s statement on its website.  
 The alleged bribe was in exchange for bidding information
on a computer-systems development program at the patent office,
Japan Times  reported .  
