 Copyright  
 Bertram Capital Unit Sued Over Royalties From Inmate’s Book  
 Bertram Capital’s XLibris unit was sued for copyright
infringement by an inmate in a Michigan correctional facility.  
 Brian Andr’e Warren, who is presently confined at the Pine
River Correctional Facility in St. Louis, Michigan, submitted a
manuscript in 2000 to  XLibris , a print-on-demand publisher.  
 He said that his work, “Through My Eye’s: Helping
Tomorrow’s Men & Women Cope with the Struggles of Today through
Jesus Christ,” has been advertised and sold through Books in
print from 2000 to 2005. He received no notice of publication
and no compensation from XLibris, according to the complaint
filed July 6 in federal court in Indianapolis.  
 Warren said he only found out by accident that this book
was being published. An exhibit he filed with his complaint is a
copy a page from the 2004-2005 edition of “Books in Print,”
which lists his book as published by XLibris with a price of $25
for the hardbound edition and $16 for a paperback.  
 According to the XLibris website , authors pay the
Bloomington, Indiana-based publisher to publish their books and
then receive royalties of 25 percent of the book’s retail price
when copies are sold through the publisher. If the book is sold
through some other channel, such as  Amazon.com Inc. ’s website,
the royalty rate is 10 percent of retail.  
 He asked the court for money damages totaling $70 million.  
 Warren is unrepresented by counsel.  
 The case is Brian Andr’e Warren v. Xlibris Corp., 1:10-cv-
00885-WTL-TAB, U.S. District Court, Southern District of Indiana
(Indianapolis).  
 Detroit’s WADL-TV Accused of Infringing ‘Remarkable Mouth’  
 Adell Broadcasting Corp., the owner of  WADL-TV  in Detroit,
was sued for copyright infringement by a California company that
creates commercials promoting radio stations.  
 Remark LLC of Los Angeles developed a series of
“Remarkable Mouth” and “Hot Lips” commercials that have been
used to promote radio stations in the U.S., according to the
complaint filed July 13 in federal court in Detroit.  
 WADL, which bills itself as “Detroit’s Urban Station,”
began broadcasting television commercials promoting itself and
featuring the “Remarkable Mouth,” Remark said in its
complaint.  
 These commercials “willfully, deliberately, and
maliciously” infringe Remark’s copyright, according to court
papers.  
 Remark asked the court for money damages, and to order
seizure and destruction of all infringing commercials, including
excerpts and outtakes. The company also requested awards of
attorney fees and litigation costs.  
 The Los Angeles company is represented by  Michael K. Grace 
of  Grace & Grace LLP  of Los Angeles.  
 The case is Remark LLC v. Adell Broadcasting Corp, 2:10-cv-
12767-GCS-MKM, U.S. District Court, Eastern District of Michigan
(Detroit).  
 Stephens Media’s Las Vegas Review-Journal Sues Over Web Posts  
 Righthaven LLC, which says it’s the holder of the copyright
for content published in the Las Vegas Review-Journal, has filed
more than 60 copyright-infringement suits since March 31.  
 The suits relate to the unauthorized posting of the
newspaper’s content on various websites.  
 Among the defendants Righthaven has sued are the National
Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws, the Democratic
Party of Nevada, the American Society of Safety Engineers, the
Motorcycle Racing Association of Nevada, and the Dr. Shezad
Malik Law Firm.  
 A number of the earlier cases have already settled for
undisclosed terms. The case against the marijuana reform group
was settled on June 4, and the case was dismissed July 9,
according to court records.  
 One of the newest cases is against Anthony Curtis, the
operator of the Las Vegas Advisor website.  
 According to a document filed with the complaint, Curtis is
accused of posting to his website an article from the Review-
Journal that is about a survey he conducted and initially
published on his own site. The survey was of prices of various
shows on the Las Vegas strip.  
 In addition to seeking money damages, litigation costs and
attorney fees, Righthaven asked the court to order it be
transferred Curtis’ domain name. Righthaven is also seeking
“all evidence and documentation relating to the names and
addresses” of anyone with whom Curtis communicated about his
use of the story from the newspaper.  
 Righthaven is represented by Steven A. Gibson and J.
Charles Coones, who are listed with no law-firm affiliation.  
 According to  the website of Las Vegas-based Stephens Media ,
it is the publisher of the Las Vegas Review-Journal, and other
newspapers in Arkansas, Hawaii, Missouri, Nevada, North
Carolina, Oklahoma, Tennessee, Texas and Washington State. The
closely held company’s website doesn’t mention Righthaven.  
 The case against Curtis is Righthaven LLC v. LVA In The
Media, 2:10-cv-01018-LRH-RJJ, U.S. District Court, District of
Nevada (Las Vegas).  
 The case against the marijuana-advocacy group is Righthaven
LLC v. National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws,
2:10-cv-00351-LDG-PAL, U.S. District Court, District of Nevada
(Las Vegas).  
