 Trademark  
 1-800 Contacts Says Standard Optical’s Keywords Infringe  
 Fenway Partners LLC’s 1-800 Contacts unit sued a Utah-based
optical company for trademark infringement.  
 Standard Optical Co. of Salt Lake City is accused of buying
keywords that confuse members of the public who are actually
searching for 1-800 Contacts website. The two companies compete
by offering contact lenses for sale over the Internet, according
to the complaint filed July 13 in federal court in Utah.  
 Affiliate networks associated with Standard Optical are
also used to misdirect potential 1-800 Contacts customers,
according to court papers. This misdirection has caused
“confusion and mistake” and falsely suggests a connection
between the two companies, 1-800 Contacts said in its pleadings.  
 In addition to asking for an order barring future
infringement of its trademarks, Draper, Utah-based 1-800
Contacts asked the court for money damages, attorney fees and
litigation costs. It also requested that the court order
Standard Optical to conduct corrective advertising.  
 1-800 Contacts is represented by  Mark A. Miller ,  Bryan G.
Pratt  and  Brett L. Foster  of  Holland & Hart LLP  of Denver.  
 The case is 1-800 Contacts Inc. v. Standard Optical Co.,
2:10-cv-00643-PMW, U.S. District Court, District of Utah.  
 ‘Basilico Genovese’ Protection Expanded by European Union  
 The European Community has approved some changes to the
protected geographical indication for Basilico Genovese,
according to  a notice  published in the Journal of the European
Union July 12.  
 The changes deal with the packaging, which includes a logo
comprised of images of the sun, the basil leaves and a map of
Liguria, which is the region in which plants accorded the
“Basilico Genovese” designation must be grown.  
 When the plant is sold fresh, it must be put in bunches
comprised of three to 10 plants with roots, and wrapped
individually in paper. It can also be sold in “bouquets”
comprised of the number of plants equivalent to 10 bunches. The
plants may have between two and four pairs of true leaves.  
 According to the plant specifications published in the
journal, Basilico Genovese has “the complete absence of minty
odor,” and contains an essential oil that is “markedly
different” from that of basil grown elsewhere.  
