 University Technology Transfer  
 University of Utah Out-Licenses Eye-Tracking Lie Detection  
 Credibility Assessment Technologies, a closely held startup
in Park City, Utah, has taken a license to lie-detection
technology developed at the University of Utah, the university
said in a  statement .  
 The invention is a method of tracking eye movement to
detect lies and was developed by Professors  John C. Kircher ,
Doug Hacker, Anne Cook,  Dan Woltz , and  David Raskin . Raskin, a
professor emeritus, is considered an expert in polygraph
techniques.  
 Eye-movement tracking measures a subject’s cognitive
reaction rather than an emotional reaction, according to the
university statement. Lying is harder work than telling the
truth, researchers found, so they look for indications in a
person’s eye movement that he is working hard.  
 Terms of the license weren’t disclosed. According to the
university statement, other potential licensees for the
technology are the U.S. Department of Defense, Customs and
Border Protection, the Department of Energy, the Department of
Homeland security and various other government agencies.  
